# How to set up your OpenClaw AI assistant on Telegram

Hi! This guide helps you set up your own AI helper that you can chat with inside Telegram. No coding background needed — just follow each step in order.

You'll use:

- **Terminal** on your Mac (the black window for typing commands — comes built in).
- **Telegram**, on whichever device you already use it on (phone, tablet, desktop, or [telegram.org](https://telegram.org) in a browser — all work the same).

The whole setup takes about 15–20 minutes. Most of that is collecting 5 keys in the next section — once you have those, the install itself is quick.

## BEFORE YOU START — get these 5 keys ready

Each key is free to start. **3 of them (Anthropic, Google AI, Brave) will ask you to add a credit card during signup**, but only Anthropic and Google AI actually charge you — usually a few cents per day for light use. Brave requires the card but stays on the free plan (you won't be billed).

Collect all 5 keys first, then come back here. Don't start the installer until the checklist at the end of this section is fully ticked.

### 1 of 5 — Telegram bot token

**What it's for:** lets your computer talk to a Telegram bot.
**Where to get it:** [BotFather on Telegram](https://t.me/BotFather)
**What it looks like:** `1234567890:ABCdef...` (a number, a colon, then letters)

![Searching for BotFather in Telegram](images/01-botfather-search.png)

1. Open Telegram, search `BotFather`, and tap the one with the blue checkmark.
2. Send `/newbot`.
3. Pick a display name, then a username ending in `bot` (e.g. `myhelperbot`).
4. Copy the long code BotFather replies with. Save it somewhere safe.

![BotFather's reply with your bot token](images/02-botfather-token.png)

### 2 of 5 — Anthropic API key

**What it's for:** lets your assistant use Claude (the AI brain).
**Where to get it:** [console.anthropic.com](https://console.anthropic.com)
**What it looks like:** `sk-ant-...`

![Anthropic sign-up page](images/03-anthropic-signup.png)

1. Go to [console.anthropic.com](https://console.anthropic.com) and sign up or log in.
2. Add a payment method. Anthropic charges per use — usually a few cents per day of light use.
3. Click **API Keys** in the menu, then **Create Key**.
4. Copy the key it shows you. **You can't see it again after closing the page** — save it somewhere safe now.

![Creating an Anthropic API key](images/04-anthropic-create-key.png)

![Copy the key — it's shown only once](images/05-anthropic-key-reveal.png)

### 3 of 5 — Firecrawl API key

**What it's for:** lets your assistant read competitor websites.
**Where to get it:** [firecrawl.dev](https://www.firecrawl.dev/)
**What it looks like:** `fc-...`

![Firecrawl dashboard](images/06-firecrawl-dashboard.png)

1. Go to [firecrawl.dev](https://www.firecrawl.dev/) and sign up (GitHub or email).
2. Once logged in, go to **Dashboard → API Keys**.
3. Click **Create API Key** and copy the key it shows you.
4. The free plan includes 500 credits per month — more than enough for normal use.

![Creating a Firecrawl API key](images/07-firecrawl-create-key.png)

### 4 of 5 — Google AI API key

**What it's for:** lets your assistant generate images for posts.
**Where to get it:** [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com/)
**What it looks like:** `AIzaSy...`

![Google AI Studio landing page](images/08-google-ai-studio.png)

1. Go to [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com/) and sign in with your Google account.
2. Click **Get API Key** in the sidebar, then **Create API Key**.
3. Pick an existing Google Cloud project, or let it create a new one.
4. Copy the key. It starts with `AIzaSy...`.
5. Enable billing at [Google Cloud Billing](https://console.cloud.google.com/billing) — image generation requires it (typically a few cents per image).

![Creating a Google AI API key](images/09-google-ai-create-key.png)

### 5 of 5 — Brave Search API key

**What it's for:** lets your assistant pull in trending news for content ideas.
**Where to get it:** [api.search.brave.com](https://api.search.brave.com/)
**What it looks like:** a long random string (no fixed prefix)

![Brave Search API dashboard](images/10-brave-dashboard.png)

1. Go to [api.search.brave.com](https://api.search.brave.com/) and click **Get Started for Free**.
2. Create an account, then go to **Dashboard → API Keys**.
3. Pick the **Free** plan (2,000 queries per month — plenty).
4. Add a credit card when prompted. Brave requires it for account verification but **will not charge you** on the Free plan.
5. Click **Generate API Key** and copy it.

![Generating a Brave Search API key](images/11-brave-generate-key.png)

### ✅ Ready to install?

| # | Key                      | Looks like            | Got it? |
|---|--------------------------|-----------------------|---------|
| 1 | Telegram bot token       | `1234...:ABC...`      |   [ ]   |
| 2 | Anthropic API key        | `sk-ant-...`          |   [ ]   |
| 3 | Firecrawl API key        | `fc-...`              |   [ ]   |
| 4 | Google AI API key        | `AIzaSy...`           |   [ ]   |
| 5 | Brave Search API key     | long random string    |   [ ]   |

If any row is empty, scroll back up and finish that one first.

The **installer** asks for keys **#1 and #2** (in Step 2). The **bot** asks for keys **#3, #4, #5** later (in Step 6).

## STEP 1 — Open Terminal

On your Mac:

- Press **Command + Space** (opens Spotlight search).
- Type: `Terminal`
- Press **Enter**.

![Opening Spotlight with Cmd+Space](images/12-terminal-spotlight.png)

A window with text will open. This is where you'll run the installer.

![Terminal window open](images/13-terminal-open.png)

## STEP 2 — Unzip the toolkit and run the installer

You received a file called `{{zip_name}}` via message.

![The toolkit zip in Finder](images/14-finder-zip.png)

1. In Finder, double-click the zip. macOS will unzip it into a folder.
2. Open the folder. Inside you'll see at least these files:

   ```
   install.sh
   install.command
   skills   (a sub-folder)
   images   (a sub-folder with screenshots)
   ```

![Unzipped toolkit folder](images/15-unzipped-folder.png)

You can start the installer in one of two ways.

> **Not sure which to pick? Use Way A.** It never triggers the "unidentified developer" pop-up that may appear with Way B.

### Way A — drag-to-Terminal (RECOMMENDED, no pop-up warnings)

1. Make sure the Terminal window from STEP 1 is open.
2. Click in the Terminal window. Type the four characters `bash` then press the SPACE BAR once. Do NOT press Enter yet.
3. Drag the file `install.sh` from the Finder folder into the Terminal window. The file's full path will appear right after `bash `.
4. Now press **Enter**.

![Dragging install.sh into Terminal](images/16-way-a-drag.png)

### Way B — double-click (simpler, but the first run triggers a macOS pop-up you have to click through)

1. In Finder, double-click `install.command`.
2. The first time you do this, macOS will almost certainly show:

   > "install.command cannot be opened because it is from an unidentified developer."

   This is NORMAL — the file is safe, it just isn't signed by Apple. To get past it:

   a. Close the pop-up.
   b. Back in Finder, right-click (or Control-click) on `install.command`.
   c. Choose **Open** from the menu.
   d. Click **Open** in the confirmation dialog.

   macOS will remember your choice. Future runs open directly.

3. A new Terminal window will open and start the installer.

![Right-click → Open on install.command](images/17-way-b-rightclick.png)

![The "unidentified developer" pop-up](images/18-way-b-gatekeeper.png)

### When the installer asks for your keys

Either way, after a few seconds the installer will stop and ask two questions. Paste from your checklist:

- **Telegram bot token:** paste key **#1** → press **Enter**.
- **Anthropic API key:** paste key **#2** → press **Enter**.

![Installer running](images/19-installer-running.png)

If you've installed OpenClaw on this Mac before, the installer also asks whether to wipe the old data first. Just press **Enter** to keep your existing data — the installer will reuse it. Type `y` and Enter only if you want a clean reinstall (this clears your saved bot connection and settings).

Wait for the installer to finish. When it's done you'll see a success message. The skills are installed automatically as part of this step — no extra command.

![Installer success](images/20-installer-success.png)

At the very end, a browser tab will open automatically — that's your **OpenClaw Control UI (dashboard)**. Don't close it; you'll use it in the next step.

## STEP 3 — Find your OpenClaw dashboard

The installer opened a browser tab titled **OpenClaw**. Switch to that tab now — it should still be open from Step 2. You don't need to do anything in it yet; just leave it open so you can glance at it while you set up the bot.

![OpenClaw dashboard opened in browser](images/21-dashboard-opened.png)

If the tab isn't there — you closed it, or the installer couldn't open it — go back to Terminal and run:

⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter:**

```
openclaw dashboard
```

That will reopen the dashboard.

## STEP 4 — Say hi to your bot

Open Telegram. In the search bar, type the bot username you chose with BotFather, and tap your bot.

📲 **Copy this and send it to your bot:**

```
hi
```

![Sending "hi" to your bot](images/22-telegram-bot-greeting.png)

The bot will reply with something like this:

```
OpenClaw: access not configured.
Your Telegram user id: 1048152213
Pairing code: 6P25BBXP

Ask the bot owner to approve with:
openclaw pairing approve telegram 6P25BBXP
```

![Bot's pairing-request reply](images/23-pairing-message.png)

Don't worry — this is expected. The bot is asking you to prove you're the owner. The next step approves it.

## STEP 5 — Approve yourself in Terminal

Look at the bot's reply above — find the **Pairing code** line (an 8-character code). Copy that code.

Go back to your Terminal window.

⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter** (replace `XXXXXXXX` with your actual pairing code):

```
openclaw pairing approve telegram XXXXXXXX
```

![Terminal showing successful approval](images/24-approval-success.png)

Terminal prints a success confirmation. Now send your bot any message — e.g. "hello" — and it will reply like a real assistant. You're paired.

## STEP 6 — Set up the content monitor

This step takes 5–10 minutes. The bot will ask **7 questions** one at a time. Have these ready before you start:

- **List of competitor websites** to monitor — or just use the default 56 pre-configured sites.
- **Facebook + X (Twitter) login** — the bot opens a browser and you log in manually. Skip either if you want to set it up later.
- **Sample post** showing your writing style (a post you've written, 100–500 words) — or skip to use a professional default.
- **Your website domain** (e.g. `www.mysite.com`) — used for internal link suggestions. Skip if you don't have one yet.
- **Preferred time + timezone** for the daily pipeline. Default is 7:00 AM Asia/Saigon.
- **Keys #3, #4, #5** from your checklist (Firecrawl, Google AI, Brave).

When you're ready, send this to your bot:

📲 **Copy this and send it to your bot:**

```
/content-monitor setup
```

![Bot starting content-monitor setup](images/25-content-monitor-setup.png)

The bot will ask the 7 questions in order. Here's what each one looks like and what to answer:

### Question 1 of 7 — Competitor websites

The bot asks what sites you want to monitor.

📲 **To use the default 56 sites, send:**

```
use defaults
```

Or paste your own list — one URL per line, like this:

```
https://www.example-competitor-1.com
https://www.example-competitor-2.com
```

The bot will then ask, for each URL, whether it's **personal-injury**, **mortgage**, or **other**.

### Question 2 of 7 — Facebook + X login

The bot opens a browser window and asks you to log into Facebook, then X (Twitter), so it can post on your behalf later. Log in manually in the browser, then tell the bot you're done.

📲 **When you've finished logging in, send:**

```
done
```

📲 **Or to skip a platform (and set it up later):**

```
skip
```

### Question 3 of 7 — Writing style sample

The bot asks for a sample of your writing so it can match your tone.

📲 **To skip and use a default professional style, send:**

```
skip
```

Or paste a post you've written before (any length — 100–500 words works best). Or paste a URL to a page that has your writing, and the bot will read it.

### Question 4 of 7 — Weekly content themes

The bot shows you a 7-day theme schedule (Monday = "Know Your Rights", Tuesday = "HEI Education", etc.).

📲 **To keep the defaults, send:**

```
keep defaults
```

Or say `customize` and the bot will walk you through each day one at a time.

### Question 5 of 7 — API keys

The bot asks for 3 keys, one at a time. You already have all three from the checklist in Section 2 — **paste all three, don't skip any**.

- **Firecrawl API key:** paste key **#3**.
- **Google AI API key:** paste key **#4**.
- **Brave Search API key:** paste key **#5**.

### Question 6 of 7 — Your website domain

📲 **Paste your domain (no `https://` needed), like:**

```
www.mysite.com
```

📲 **Or skip if you don't have one yet:**

```
skip
```

### Question 7 of 7 — Daily schedule

The bot asks what time to run the daily content pipeline.

📲 **For the default (7:00 AM Asia/Saigon), send:**

```
default
```

Or enter your own time, like `7:00 AM` or `08:30`. The bot will then ask for your timezone — send `default` for Asia/Saigon, or enter one like `America/Los_Angeles` or `Europe/London`.

### After all 7 questions

The bot automatically sets up the workspace folders, does a first-time crawl of all competitor sites (takes a few minutes), and sends you a summary. You're done — the daily pipeline will now run on the schedule you picked.

## STEP 7 — Test that it works

📲 **Copy this and send it to your bot:**

```
run content pipeline
```

![Bot reporting a successful test run](images/26-test-run-result.png)

You should see the monitor run and report back what it found. Done! 🎉

## Troubleshooting

**"Permission denied" when running install.sh**

- Use Way A from STEP 2: open Terminal, type `bash` and a space, then drag `install.sh` into Terminal, then press Enter.
- This works even if the file lost its permission to run during unzip.

**install.command won't open — "unidentified developer" pop-up**

- Right-click (or Control-click) on `install.command` in Finder.
- Choose **Open**, then click **Open** in the confirmation dialog.
- macOS will remember your choice after that.

**Unzipping didn't create a folder**

- Try double-clicking the zip again in Finder — macOS's built-in Archive Utility is the most reliable. Avoid third-party unzip apps.

**The browser tab with the dashboard didn't open**

- Go to Terminal and run:

  ⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter:**

  ```
  openclaw dashboard
  ```

**I don't want the dashboard to auto-open on install**

- Re-run the installer with this in front:

  ⌨️ **Paste this into Terminal and press Enter** (replace the path with your actual install.sh path):

  ```
  OPENCLAW_NO_DASHBOARD=1 bash /path/to/install.sh
  ```

**The bot doesn't reply**

- Make sure you completed STEP 5 (approval).
- Check that you're messaging the right bot (the one you made with BotFather).

**"invalid Telegram bot token format"**

- The token should look like `123456789:AA...` (a number, a colon, then letters/numbers).
- Re-copy it from BotFather and try again.

**"invalid Anthropic API key"**

- The key must start with `sk-ant-`.
- Re-copy it from [console.anthropic.com](https://console.anthropic.com) and try again.

**"skills/ not found next to install.sh"**

- The zip was unzipped incompletely or the `skills` folder was moved.
- Re-unzip the original zip file and run the installer from inside the fresh folder.

**Something else**

- Copy the error message and ask for help.

## 📖 What you can say to your bot

A quick reference of messages the bot understands. Send any of these in Telegram like a normal chat message.

### General

| Say this               | What happens                                       |
|------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|
| `hi`                   | Greets the bot. First time, triggers pairing.      |
| any free-text message  | Regular AI-assistant reply.                        |

### Content monitor

| Say this                   | What happens                                         |
|----------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|
| `/content-monitor setup`   | Starts guided first-time setup.                      |
| `setup content monitor`    | Same as above, plain-English version.                |
| `run content pipeline`     | Runs the pipeline once so you can verify it works.   |
| `approve`                  | Approves the most recent draft the bot showed you.   |
| `what's new today?`        | Asks the monitor for today's topic suggestions.      |

Add more bot skills later? Come back and check this section.

## Keep these safe

Your 5 keys (Telegram bot token, Anthropic, Firecrawl, Google AI, Brave) are like passwords. Don't share them publicly — screenshots, chats, emails, or code repositories. If one leaks, regenerate it on the provider's dashboard:

- Telegram bot token → [BotFather](https://t.me/BotFather)
- Anthropic → [console.anthropic.com](https://console.anthropic.com)
- Firecrawl → [firecrawl.dev](https://www.firecrawl.dev/)
- Google AI → [aistudio.google.com](https://aistudio.google.com/)
- Brave Search → [api.search.brave.com](https://api.search.brave.com/)
